result.msg:
Welcome to Zeppelin.

This is a live tutorial, you can run the code yourself. (Shift-Enter to Run)

In this short tutorial we will load some data from Python and query it from SQL & Scala. Compared to Jupyter, Zeppelin provides a better integration with Spark, in particular it

  • allows multiple languages (i.e. Python, Scala & SQL) to share the same Spark context within a notebook;
  • comes out of the box with a Spark progress bar;
  • allows the current Spark job to be cancelled;
  • comes with simple plotting tools that are particularly attractive when combined with SQL.

Jupyter is still king in other areas, like auto-completion and matplotlib support, for which Zeppelin has only a basic support. Furthermore, neither RTMO nor Github can render Zeppelin notebooks yet.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark 

from moztelemetry import get_pings_properties
from moztelemetry.dataset import Dataset

pings = Dataset.from_source("telemetry") \
    .where(docType='main') \
    .where(submissionDate="20170224") \
    .where(appUpdateChannel="nightly") \
    .records(sc, sample=0.1)
    
subset = get_pings_properties(pings, ["environment/system/os/name",
                                      "payload/simpleMeasurements/firstPaint"])
                                      
subset.toDF().createOrReplaceTempView("nightly_sample")

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

from moztelemetry.zeppelin import show

fig = plt.figure()
frame = pd.DataFrame(subset.collect())
np.log(frame["payload/simpleMeasurements/firstPaint"]).plot(kind="hist", bins=100)
show(plt)

%md

As the SparkContext is shared between different interpreters once a temporary view has been registered it can be accessed by SparkSQL and Scala. A visualization toolbox will appear automatically when running a SparkSQL query.

paragraphs.text:
%sql 

select `environment/system/os/name`, count(*)
from nightly_sample
group by 1

%md 

Just as we can access temporary views any other table registered within the Hive metastore can be access as well, like the *longitudinal* one.

result.msg: Just as we can access temporary views any other table registered within the Hive metastore can be access as well, like the longitudinal one.

paragraphs.text:
%sql
with submissions as (
  select explode(build) as build
  from longitudinal
  where build is not null
), grouped as (
  select build.architecture as arch, count(*) as total
  from submissions
  group by 1
)
select arch, 100 * total / sum(total) over () as percentage
from grouped
order by 2 desc
limit 2
